00:31:03.710 --> 00:31:07.110
In terms of the kind of acoustics
experiments, I could, you know,

00:31:07.110 --> 00:31:08.460
have a whole talk just on those.

00:31:08.460 --> 00:31:11.730
But one of the most interesting
ones with the swiss cheese violin,

00:31:11.730 --> 00:31:15.900
where she punched 64 holes
in the ribs of the instrument

00:31:15.900 --> 00:31:18.410
and then plugged those
holes of cotton.

00:31:18.410 --> 00:31:20.240
Then, she would remove the cotton.

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:24.570
And she and Saunders were
exploring really the violin

00:31:24.570 --> 00:31:25.960
as a wind instrument.

00:31:25.960 --> 00:31:27.260
You think of them.

00:31:27.260 --> 00:31:28.950
They start out studying
the wood modes.

00:31:28.950 --> 00:31:30.250
They want to see how
the wood's vibrating.

00:31:30.250 --> 00:31:32.910
And then they realized that maybe
the air currents inside the box are

00:31:32.910 --> 00:31:34.420
far more important.

00:31:34.420 --> 00:31:38.070
So that was one interesting
experiment.

00:31:38.070 --> 00:31:40.370
Yes.

