00:32:17.630 --> 00:32:20.240
So one of the issues with
the acoustics is, as I said,

00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:26.590
in order for the instrument to
have the same acoustical properties

00:32:26.590 --> 00:32:30.330
as the violin, it would need
to be about 20 inches long.

00:32:30.330 --> 00:32:31.630
So one of the things --

00:32:31.630 --> 00:32:34.230
And surprisingly, this
viola doesn't have these.

00:32:34.230 --> 00:32:36.430 position:56%
One of the things that we experience

00:32:36.430 --> 00:32:39.470
as string players is
called a wolf tone.

00:32:39.470 --> 00:32:41.900
Violins don't often have them.

00:32:41.900 --> 00:32:44.070
I was the unfortunate
owner of a violin

00:32:44.070 --> 00:32:47.920
with a very bad wolf
tone for many years.

00:32:47.920 --> 00:32:51.880
And my viola that I have
has a wolf tone as well.

00:32:51.880 --> 00:32:55.610
In the past few years, a
little device has been invented

00:32:55.610 --> 00:32:57.780
that gets rid of these wolf tones.

00:32:57.780 --> 00:33:02.770 position:56%
But really, when you use a wolf tone
eliminator or something like that,

00:33:02.770 --> 00:33:05.510 position:56%
it does damp the sound a little bit.

00:33:05.510 --> 00:33:07.390
So --

00:33:07.390 --> 00:33:08.810
&gt;&gt; Quincy Whitney: And I
would just add to that,

00:33:08.810 --> 00:33:11.160
the wolf tone was also
something that Hutchins

00:33:11.160 --> 00:33:14.720
and Saunders were studying a lot,
what makes them happen and why

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:16.400
and when they're really bad.

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:19.730
And sometimes you can't
do anything about them.

00:33:19.730 --> 00:33:21.030
&gt;&gt; Shannon Merlino: Right.

00:33:21.030 --> 00:33:24.010
The sound of the instrument is
produced by two different forces.

00:33:24.010 --> 00:33:28.320
The resonating body of
air inside the instrument

00:33:28.320 --> 00:33:30.660
and also the resonance of
the plates in the back.

00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:35.610
So, you know, it's just my guess.

00:33:35.610 --> 00:33:38.170
I don't have anything
to back this up.

00:33:38.170 --> 00:33:42.010 position:56%
But because of the shape and the
dimensions of Carleen's instruments,

00:33:42.010 --> 00:33:44.560
they do avoid some of
those issues that come up.

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:46.860
So does that answer?

00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:50.070
&gt;&gt; Quincy Whitney: With
respect to playing them,

00:33:50.070 --> 00:33:55.130
I know that she had an experience
many times when a player would come

00:33:55.130 --> 00:33:56.430
to one of her instruments

00:33:56.430 --> 00:33:58.460
and immediately start
putting a particular pressure

00:33:58.460 --> 00:34:01.070
that a cellist might
put on his cello.

00:34:01.070 --> 00:34:05.720 position:56%
And she had to pull them all off and
just say go much lighter and listen

00:34:05.720 --> 00:34:08.160
to what the instrument can
do because lots of times,

00:34:08.160 --> 00:34:10.620
you come to an instrument
with an expectation

00:34:10.620 --> 00:34:12.410
about how much pressure
you have to add.

00:34:12.410 --> 00:34:16.390
And she was always trying to get
them to lighten up because she did

00:34:16.390 --> 00:34:19.840
so much work on the resonance
of both the box and the wood

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:23.290
that it started to sing
with less pressure.

